---
/**
 * Standalone claim that leads into the Método Zil section. It reads as the head
 * of that section rather than a section of its own — but the #how-we-work anchor
 * lives on Método Zil itself, so "Cómo trabajamos" lands on the mark, not here.
 *
 * Spacing is deliberately asymmetric, and that is the rhythm working, not
 * drifting: `pt-section` gives the standard half-gap above (Projects supplies
 * the matching half), while below is ZERO. Método Zil is viewport-pinned — its
 * stage is min-h-100svh with centred content, so it already opens with
 * (100svh − content) / 2 of space above its logo, measured at ~264px on a
 * 375×812 phone. Any padding added here is stacked on top of that, which is
 * exactly what made this seam read as lopsided (128px above vs 312px below).
 * Let the pinned stage own the space below; do not add `pb-*` here.
 */
---

<section>
  <div
    class="mx-auto w-full max-w-8xl px-6 pt-section text-center tablet:px-8 desktop:px-12"
    data-reveal-group
  >
    {
      /* The marker-highlighted closing clause must always read as one unbroken
        band, so it carries `whitespace-nowrap`. That makes type size the binding
        constraint on mobile: the clause measures ~9.9px wide per 1px of font
        size, so at text-h2 it needs 342px — which fits a 390px screen exactly,
        with zero slack, and overflows every narrower phone. Hence the scale
        starts a step down: text-h3 holds it on one line to a 320px screen, and
        tablet/desktop have the room for the bigger steps. If the copy changes,
        re-check the mobile width before trusting the nowrap.

        Balancing is deliberately tablet-and-up. From tablet the clause still
        flows inline after the lead and balancing reads well, but on mobile the
        nowrap span is an atomic box wider than any word, and the balancer drags
        the preceding word onto its line to compensate — leaving that line far
        longer than the two above it (318 vs 192/204 at 390px), which is the
        opposite of balanced. Plain wrapping drops the clause onto its own line
        as a clean band instead.

        The relaxed leading is required: an inline background covers the font's
        content area (~1.26em), which is taller than the h1 token's own 1.05
        line-height, so without it the block collides with the line above. */
    }
    {
      /* Entrance — the one signature move on the page, and the reason it is here
        rather than anywhere else: this sentence IS the site's thesis, and the
        marker band is the "dirección clara" it is talking about. So the clause
        opens as reserved white space, the band strokes across it left to right,
        and the lime words arrive inside as it lands. The claim and the gesture
        are the same thing.

        The band is painted by growing `background-size`, never by transforming
        this span, and every constraint in the note above is why: the clause is
        measured to the pixel, `whitespace-nowrap` makes it atomic, and the inline
        background is what forces the relaxed leading. transform/clip-path would
        need the span to stop being inline and put all of that back in play.
        background-size moves nothing at any width. Details in reveal.ts.

        `bg-primary-dark` stays on the span so no-JS and reduced-motion readers get
        the finished band from the class alone; the engine's gradient paints the
        same colour and hands it back on completion. */
    }
    {
      /* `inline-block` (not the plain `inline` this once was) because the band
        ROTATES its word, and `width` has no effect on an inline box — the engine
        pins the span to the widest word so the line never re-centres and "clara
        es" never shifts. `whitespace-nowrap` keeps it an atomic, unbroken band.

        The word list is the source of truth for the rotation; `data-band-text`
        holds the FIRST word statically so no-JS and reduced-motion readers get a
        finished, meaningful sentence from the markup alone. Keep the two in sync:
        data-band-text must equal the first entry of data-band-words. */
    }
    <h2
      class="text-[30px] leading-[1.3] tracking-[-0.03em] tablet:text-h2 tablet:text-balance desktop:text-h1"
      data-reveal
    >
      Una comunicación visual clara es <span
        class="inline-block bg-primary-dark px-3 whitespace-nowrap text-left text-accent"
        data-reveal="band"
        data-reveal-delay="0.45"
        data-band-words='["crecimiento.", "estrategia.", "diferenciación."]'
        ><span data-band-text>crecimiento.</span></span
      >
    </h2>
  </div>
</section>
